Using 164 H5N1 hemagglutinin (HA) gene sequences (NCBI Influenza Virus Resource) from samples spanning five different geographic locales (Egypt, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Thailand, and Vietnam), we generated a multiple alignment and consensus sequence for each locale using MUSCLE [21]. We then created a multiple alignment of the five consensus sequences, in order to index the nucleotides across all sequences uniformly. To find regions of low variation within a locale, we used an information theory approach. We set a window size of k = 5 nucleotides, and for each index, we calculated the k-mer (words of length k) sequence entropy using the standard entropy equation [18]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
